â€œAs a Black African woman I practice intersectional environmentalism as it draws on the inextricable interconnectedness of marginalised communities and the planet and purposely prioritises people and the planet. Over the years I've adopted more sustainable ways of living and my health and general well being, which is synonymous to that of the Earth, has thanked me for it. I wear low waste clothing, use a biodegradable products (like bamboo toothbrushes), support tree planting initiatives in my community, buy local produce from clothing to fruit, and purposely engage in increasing my eco consciousness by learning and unlearning from other climate activists across the globe."â£
